# LingoLeaf Coding + Commenting Rules

## Comment style
- Use `//` comments only (do not use block comments).
- Add comments above functions, not inline-by-default.
- Keep comments short (1-3 lines), practical, and focused on:
  - what the function does
  - how it is used
  - why it exists (user/UX or architectural reason)
  - (Exception: `extension/lib/` named functions also use Params/Returns lines as in **Lib function contracts** below.)
- Prefer intent-level comments over line-by-line logic narration.
- Avoid obvious comments and avoid restating code syntax.

## Lib function contracts (`extension/lib/`)
- Above every **named** function (including nested helpers), document **inputs** and **return value** using `//` lines.
- Use explicit labels so it scans quickly, for example:
  - `// Params: ...` (types or shapes in plain language: string, string[], object fields)
  - `// Returns: ...` (type + meaning; note `null`, empty string, or thrown errors when relevant)
- One-line intent summary may precede Params/Returns; keep the whole block compact (avoid JSDoc `/** */`).

## Refactoring boundaries
- Keep `background.js` focused on Chrome extension orchestration:
  - event listeners
  - storage reads/writes
  - mode toggles / context-menu wiring
- Move pure logic into `extension/lib/` as reusable functions:
  - text normalization
  - heuristics/threshold checks
  - parsing/validation helpers
- Keep pure helpers deterministic and side-effect free.

## API/service organization
- Keep network/API calls out of orchestration when possible.
- Put LLM/API interactions in service modules (e.g. `ollama-api.js`).
- Keep prompt construction separate from API call plumbing.
- Store prompt text in named constants/builders, not long inline strings in handlers.

## Data flow conventions
- Keep save/translate flows resilient:
  - fail soft and preserve user action where possible
  - fallback to simpler behavior if segmentation/parsing fails
- Keep list storage updates explicit and predictable (`chrome.storage.local`).

## UI logic conventions
- Share UI behavior across popup and sidepanel via common scripts/styles when feasible.
- Keep markup differences minimal and intentional (mode-specific controls/hints only).

## JavaScript style
- Do not use semicolons at end-of-line in JavaScript, ever (omit `;` after statements).

## Agent workflow (git + prompts)
- Before running git commands that may **update the working tree**, **reset/revert** files, or **create commits**, confirm the current **branch** (and intended ref) and prefer giving the user exact commands to run themselves unless they asked the agent to run git.
- When a prompt is **ambiguous or underspecified** for implementation, **ask clarifying questions before** making code or file changes.
